    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2440933766" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2440933766" />
    <a title="Fergus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70395042-fergus"><img alt="Fergus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624317933p2/70395042.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2440933766?book_show_action=true">Mar 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fergus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fergus" href="/user/show/70395042-fergus">Fergus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/26700207-a-death-in-the-family">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2440933766" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7895320409829610868">Until my GR friend Roger recently published his review of this book, I had forgotten I read it, many years ago. <br/><br/>It used to sit in a corner of my office desk in 1973, a few months after my graduation.<br/><br/>The experience of that office, like reading Agee’s short and remarkable book, was filled with my attempts to find my youth in the wasteland of the spirit which is the modern workplace. <br/><br/>But I could find neither a respite from my ragged dreams of adulthood, nor the fulfillment of my magical childhood v</span>
  <span id="freeText7895320409829610868" style="display:none">Until my GR friend Roger recently published his review of this book, I had forgotten I read it, many years ago. <br /><br />It used to sit in a corner of my office desk in 1973, a few months after my graduation.<br /><br />The experience of that office, like reading Agee’s short and remarkable book, was filled with my attempts to find my youth in the wasteland of the spirit which is the modern workplace. <br /><br />But I could find neither a respite from my ragged dreams of adulthood, nor the fulfillment of my magical childhood visions, in either.<br /><br />For after the initial rhapsodic dreams of the novel, or of childhood, the wasteland reigns. And day turns to night! <br /><br />And with the workplace I entered Nightworld too. Because I had never properly awakened to adulthood.<br /><br />Once you do wake up, there is no turning back. I just kept on looking over my shoulder, at the past.<br /><br />And it had all begun a little over ten years earlier...<br /><br />I was about to turn thirteen. My biological makeup was changing, and a dimension of stress was being added to my prepubescent chemistry. <br /><br />One morning, before my parents and siblings awoke, I drowsily traced the outlines of female actresses from the newspaper onto tracing paper in the predawn hours. <br /><br />I had no clue why I was doing it. I only knew it was somehow being demanded of me.<br /><br />A few nights later, the unexplained urges came at night. <br /><br />Again I started resisting something which was apparently required. But then I started thinking rashly. <br /><br />Without warning my thought was interrupted by my father’s voice, from the living room. “Sounds like you can’t sleep. Can I bring you a glass of water?” <br /><br />I was mortified. <br /><br />And I refused his kind offer, obviously. Perhaps it was that in the past a voice from the main room meant Punishment. My head was suddenly filled with self-directed embarrassment.<br /><br />Reduced to shocked and embarrassed silence, I made a vow then and there to fight this Thing, whatever it was. <br /><br />But I had bitten into the Apple. Life would never be the same. I had COME OF AGE - and had SEEN THROUGH MYSELF. For at that hideous moment I MYSELF was the Serpent.<br /><br />And thereupon I was struck blind to the appearance of folks around me, who had emerged from a similar awakening quite differently changed.<br /><br />So thereafter I always tried to do good enthusiastically - and was just as crestfallen and beaten up by my better judgment as I was at that moment, whenever I failed.<br /><br />So after my Dad went back to his TV set, after calling out to me, I felt strangely straitened. <br /><br />Straitened like someone - yes, exactly like the person - who has perforce chosen the strait and narrow path for his OWN. What choice did I have?<br /><br />Now, it’s funny, for I would later take this Rising Above that I chose, to be a way of transcendence. <br /><br />But, you know, that very feeling of straitening transcendence can be a very real mistake.<br /><br />Either we grow up or we remain primly childish inside.<br /><br />I’ll tell you a story: You know, a would-be patient one day approached Sigmund Freud for a cure to his manic hysteria. Freud said, “Well, I can’t CURE you - but I CAN turn your hysteria into something more like ordinary human misery...”<br /><br />Freud was right. Life ISN’T more fun than a barrel of monkeys. In fact, it’s tough.<br /><br />We WON’T get through life sensitively by always forcing ourselves to be happier.<br /><br />If we grow up and face the music, though, we WILL find Real Love and Meaning in this bitter life. <br /><br />But that inner child of ours has gotta go. For a while.<br /><br />And we won’t feel love unless we first feel real disappointment in ourselves - <br /><br />For we won’t ever be perfect ourselves, no matter how hard we try -<br /><br />But Love Already Is perfect.<br /><br />And if we just accept ordinary life as it is, it can be beautiful... and it will henceforth ALWAYS SURPRISE (and shock?) US.<br /><br />And then, the Light of Old Age will glow all the brighter for our own, and the world's, Darkness all around it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7895320409829610868" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


