<div id="review_243373097" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/243373097" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1385615-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611291805p2/1385615.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/243373097?book_show_action=true">Dec 05, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/1385615-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143115847" href="/book/show/5533407-a-death-in-the-family">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer243373097" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2951437907886169879">I was really looking forward to this book. It is spoken of so highly, was graced with a Pulitzer Prize and published posthumously after the untimely death of its young author. However I waited in vain for it to catch fire and was quite disappointed overall. It clearly packed much more of a wallop when first printed but now seems rather dated and less powerful than it once was. At least to me.<br/><br/>Certainly there are lyric passages of great beauty, the most famous of which would be the introductory &quot;K</span>
  <span id="freeText2951437907886169879" style="display:none">I was really looking forward to this book. It is spoken of so highly, was graced with a Pulitzer Prize and published posthumously after the untimely death of its young author. However I waited in vain for it to catch fire and was quite disappointed overall. It clearly packed much more of a wallop when first printed but now seems rather dated and less powerful than it once was. At least to me.<br /><br />Certainly there are lyric passages of great beauty, the most famous of which would be the introductory "Knoxville: Summer of 1915". But even that was improved upon when Samuel Barber famously set it to music as a commission for the great American soprano Eleanor Steber. Agee's descriptions of nature, light and shadow, and the sounds one hears (or does not hear, in the case of the numerous nearly-deaf characters) are most successful. I was much less taken with his dialogue and character portrayals, one exception being the deliciously malevolent Father Jackson.<br /><br />Agee talked of pursuing an improvisational writing style akin to Jazz music. That is certainly apparent in many places with the repetition of sentence fragments or his playful riffs on certain phrases. Characters repeat themselves, altering their expressions by replacing a single word or "changing keys" by varying the emotion behind their words rather than the words themselves.<br /><br />Had this been applied to a story I found more interesting, involving people I liked, I'm sure I would feel differently. Instead the whole thing just plodded along and was a chore to get through. I was anticipating "Lush Life" and all I got was "Three Blind Mice".</span>
  <a data-text-id="2951437907886169879" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


